CHIKUNGUNYA (06): GERMANY ex INDONESIA (BALI) 2012
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 27 Feb 2013
From: Patrick Vollmar <PatrickVollmar@bundeswehr.org> [edited]


In December 2012 a 53-year-old female traveller developed fever with headache, arthralgia, and exanthema in combination with lymphadenopathy and mild hepatitis 3 days after returning from an 18 day trip to Bali. Laboratory diagnostics of the blood sample, taken one day after onset of symptoms, showed leucocytopenia, thrombocytopenia, and mildly elevated transaminases.

Whereas serological investigation revealed negative results for chikungunya and dengue virus, the PCR-result for chikungunya virus was positive. The virus strain could successfully be isolated by cell culture; molecular characterization of the isolated chikungunya virus is in progress.

A serological follow up specimen 47 days after the 1st examination showed seroconversion for chikungunya virus with high titres for IgM- and IgG-antibodies while no serological evidence for a coinfection with dengue virus was found.

The patient had direct flights from Germany to Bali and back without a stay in any other chikungunya virus-endemic area. She predominantly stayed in the coastal region around Semenyak with excursions in the regions around Ubud. She reported several mosquito bites during her holidays but no clinical symptoms in Bali. Currently the patient still complains of headaches and arthralgia.

While chikungunya fever cases in Indonesia seem to be frequent in Central and Western Java, there have been only sporadic reports from Bali so far (see ProMED-mail posting 20080720.2198). Healthcare authorities should be aware of the ongoing occurrence of chikungunya fever in Bali. Travellers should be advised to apply preventive measures (such as, protection from mosquito bites).

--
